      <lg type="edition">
<l>muṭkāṟ kārai mutupaḻa ṉēyppat</l>
<l>teṟippa viḷainta tīṅkan tāra</l>
<l>niṟutta vāyan talaiceṉ ṟuṇṭu</l>
<l>paccūṉ ṟiṉṟu painniṇam perutta</l>
<l>vecci līrṅkai viṟpuṟan timirip</l>
<l>pulampuk kaṉaṉē pullaṇaṟ kāḷai</l>
<l>yorumuṟai yuṇṇā vaḷavaip perunirai</l>
<l>yūrppuṟa niṟaiyat tarukuvaṉ yārkkun</l>
<l>toṭuta lōmpumati mutukaṭ cāṭi</l>
<l>yāttarak kaḻumiya tukaḷaṉ</l>
<l>kāytalu muṇṭak kaḷvey yōṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
  Going at the head of a herd he balanced
against the sweet licquor fully(?) matured
so as to resemble the old fruits of thorny-stemmed Kārai,
	drinking,
eating fresh meat, smearing the back of [his] bow
with [his] hand moist with the leftovers that are thick with fresh fat
he entered the fields [again], the young man with a ruddy beard. 
Before eating a single time he will bring a big heard,
so that the outside of the village is full, for everyone.
Beware of touching the old-mouthed jar 
of him who is keen on that toddy, drinking as soon as he is thirsty,
he with dust that is copious as he brings the cows.
</lg>
